A nominee director is an individual appointed to act as a director of a company, on behalf of another organization or individual (the "nominee"). The nominee director does not normally attend board meetings or have a direct involvement in the decision-making process of the company, but is responsible for providing corporate governance and representation.
A company may appoint nominee directors if they wish to remain anonymous or if they are unable or unwilling to disclose complete details in respect of their involvement with the business. Historically, this practice has been very common in offshore jurisdictions such as the British Virgin Islands and Isle of Man.
Nominee directors are usually appointed by a professional third-party known as a "corporate nominee". The services of a corporate nominee are usually required if the individual or organization wants to remain anonymous, as the nominee will be solely responsible for all decision making. In this case, the nominee holds the required management and decision-making responsibilities which are usually reserved for officers and directors of the company. 
The corporate nominee may be expected to:
• Provide advice and expertise on areas such as company formation, corporate registration and filing, business registration and taxation;
• Assist with corporate governance matters;
• Take part in making decisions related to the direction and operation of the company;
• Act as the point of contact for the shareholders and other corporate associates.
The terms of appointment and responsibilities for a nominee director may vary according to the customer's requirements and the jurisdiction in which the company is registered. In some cases, the nominee may be required to sign all legal documents, and in others, the signatory may be the customer or, if appropriate, use a power of attorney.

